@node Introduction "JustComm documentation - Introduction"
@{b}Introduction
------------@{ub}

    JustComm is a CLI based utility to change filenotes of multiple files.
    F.ex. change letters from lowercase to uppercase, replace substrings, add substrings, etc.
@endnode
  

@node Features "JustComm documentation - Features"
@{b}Features
--------@{ub}

    * Convert letters to uppercase or lowercase.

    * Misc. "uppercase options":
        * Make 1st. letter uppercase.
        * Make 1st. letter after a character uppercase
          (the user can specify one or more such characters).
        * Make roman numerals uppercase (ex: xvIi -> XVII).

    * Flexible filters:
        * Perform actions on selected substrings.
        * Perform actions before or after a substring.
        * Case sensitive or case insensitive pattern matching.

    * Replace filenotes (or parts of it, if a filter is used).

    * Insert new text:
       * At the start or after the end.
       * Before or after a chosen filter.

    * Remove CTRL-characters. These are characters which are displayed
      as strange and meaningless characters, like f.ex squares.

    * Align according to a selected substring.
 
    * Export to a file in a fileformat that PC programs like "Total Commander" accepts.
      This makes it possible to let "Total Commander" show the filenotes.
      It's also useful for backup purposes.

    * Import from a file (the same file format as above). This comes in handy when:
         * copying files from poor file systems which doesn't support filenotes,
           and store the notes on your Amiga as real filenotes (nothing beats the real thing, eh?).
         * efficiently mass-update filenotes based on other sources, like f.ex. URL's etc.
         * you need to restore your filenotes (backup).

    * Can perform multiple actions on filenotes in one go (&&-option),
      which otherwise had to be done via several calls to JustComm.
      This is also more efficient, since each filenote will not be written to disk
      more than once (except when using the IMP and -g options).

    * Most of the features above can be combined together.

    * Supports filenames up to 108 characters.

    * Very efficient processing.
@endnode


@node Requirements "JustComm documentation - Requirements"
@{b}Requirements
------------@{ub}
    
    It will work on:
    * Any Classic Amiga with at least a 68000 processor, and at least Kickstart 1.3.
    * Any Amiga with OS4.1 (via JIT emulation). The speed is remarkably fast here too!


    It has been tested on classic amigas:
    
       1) from CLI and Directory Opus 4 on Amigas using standard filesystem:
          * A500  / 0.5MB Fast / Kickstart 1.3
          * A1200 / Blizzard 1230 / 32MB Fast / Kickstart 3.1 / 40GB HD
 
       2) with Directory Opus 5 using standard filesystem:
          * A1200 / Blizzard 1230 / 32MB Fast / Kickstart 3.1 / 40GB HD    


    ...and a PPC-equipped Amiga with OS4.1:
 
       1) from CLI and Directory Opus 4 on Amiga using OFS/SFS00/SFS02/JXSF filesystems:
          * Sam440EP / 512MB / OS4.1 / 30GB OCZ Solid State Drive
@endnode


@node Usage "JustComm documentation - Usage"
@{b}Usage
-----@{ub}
    @{fg text}@{b}JustComm@{ub} [-<@{"options" link Options}>] [<@{"advanced options" link Advanced_Options}>] "@{"<filename>" link Filenames}"@{fg text}

    Notes: - The [] symbols means the options within are optional.
           - The <> symbols represent real options like f.ex. f.
           - The options and advanced options can be placed wherever you like, except between filenames.
           - More than 1 file can be chosen. F.ex.: "file1" "file2" "fileN".
           - It's advised to specify the options first and files last,
             when starting JustComm from Directory Opus.
    
    Note: When starting JustComm without arguments, it will display
          the Usage and available arguments.
          The same thing happens if there is an error in the argument string
          (with a few exceptions).

    An example of the usage is found @{"here" link Complete_Example}.

    Directory Opus 5 users: Have a look @{"here" link Opus5_users}.
@endnode


@node  Opus5_users "JustComm documentation - Usage - Directory Opus 5"
@{b}Directory Opus 5 users
----------------------@{ub}

    IMPORTANT: Directory Opus might start AmigaDOS commands more than once.
               This happens when the argument string (including the filename list)
               contains more bytes than the AmigaDOS argument buffer can store (max 512 Bytes).
               This also counts for Directory Opus 4.
               In such cases it's best to first create a file with all filenames in it,
               and use this file as an input to JustComm (input redirection).

    IMPORTANT: Because of the same problem as mentioned above, you should always place
               the filenames at the end of the argument list.
               This way, when/if the size of the argument string exceeds the maximum limit,
               Directory Opus will split the argument string correctly.
               If the filenames are placed last, you ensure that it's only the filename-list
               that's getting splitted instead of the options.
               If you don't do this, unexpected results may occur, like the error messages
               "missing args !", "wrong args !", etc.

    @{b}@{u}Tips regarding the included buttons:@{uu}@{ub}
      * See the attached screenshot.

      * The label of each button explains what it does.

      * Most buttons prompts for a substring to search for, if the right mouse-button is pressed.

      * Import-button:
        Imports filenotes from a file.

      * Export-button:
        Exports filenotes to a file.
        PS: If filenotes contains LF-characters, all text after the LF-character will be moved
            to the next line in the export file.
            This may cause compatibility issues with other programs.
            To avoid problems, it's recommended to always remove CTRL-characters before export.

      * Split words with ' '-button:
        Strings like "MyCommand" or "helloWorld" will be changed to "My Command" and "hello World".

      * Auto-button: Try it out! 
        Changes filenotes according to a set of predefined rules.

      * Custom-button: Use this if you want to type in the options directly.
        Useful if you need to do something that is not covered by the other buttons.
@endnode


@node Complete_Example "JustComm documentation - Usage - Complete Example"
@{b}A complete example:
-------------------@{ub}
    
    Suppose we have 2 files in the RAM-disk with these filenotes:
     
      1) a CoMPlEte TEST
      2) boUldErDasH_iv.dMS


    ..and we want them to look like this:

      1) A complete test
      2) Boulderdash_IV.DMS


    ..we can achieve this by typing:
        @{fg fill}JustComm "RAM:|*|" -1lr && SEL=".|*|" -u@{fg text}


    Explanation:

      "RAM:|*|" - Select all files in the RAM-disk
      -1lr      - Convert characters to lowercase, except
                  the first character and the roman numerals, 
                  which is converted to uppercase.
      && SEL    - After the options above has been performed, 
                  the string ".dMS" is converted to uppercase.
@endnode


@node Installation "JustComm documentation - Installation"
@{b}Installation
------------@{ub}
    
    Simply copy the file JustComm into your @{fg fill}C@{fg text} directory.

    @{b}@{u}Directory Opus 5 users:@{uu}@{ub}
    I have included a buttonbank with the most common functions.
    To use these buttons:
       1) Make sure you have a directory named @{fg fill}T@{fg text} in your @{fg fill}RAM-disk@{fg text}.
          If it's missing, add this to your @{fg fill}user-startup@{fg text} file (@{fg fill}S:user-startup@{fg text}):
            @{fg fill}IF NOT EXISTS RAM:T
               Makedir RAM:T
            ENDIF@{fg text}
       2) Copy the file @{fg fill}JustComm_buttons@{fg text} into your @{fg fill}Dopus5:buttons@{fg text} directory.
       3) Copy the file @{fg fill}echo_noLF@{fg text} into your @{fg fill}C@{fg text} directory
       4) Copy the file @{fg fill}ArgListTMP.script@{fg text} into your @{fg fill}S@{fg text} directory,
          and set the file's "script" protection bit (Lha doesn't seem to preserve this).
       5) Start Opus5 and then open the @{fg fill}JustComm_buttons@{fg text}.
          A window with buttons will now appear.

    @{b}Tip@{ub}: The commands echo_noLF and ArgListTMP.script files can also be used with other commands.
           Comes in handy with Directory Opus to avoid CLI-commands being started more frequently
           than necessary.
@endnode


@node Options "JustComm documentation - Usage - Options"
@{b}    Options:
    --------@{ub}

       @{"  u  " link u_Details}       Make letters uppercase
       @{"  l  " link l_Details}       Make letters lowercase
       @{"  1  " link 1_Details}       Make 1st. letter uppercase
       @{"  r  " link r_Details}       Make roman numbers uppercase (M,D,C,L,X,V,I)
       @{"  t  " link t_Details}       Remove CTRL-characters
       @{"  f  " link f_Details}       Copy filename to filenote
       @{"  b  " link b_Details}       Before
       @{"  a  " link a_Details}       After
       @{"  i  " link i_Details}       Insert
       @{"  g  " link g_Details}       Align
       @{"  S  " link Sens_Details}       Case Sensitive pattern matching
       @{"  e  " link e_Details}       Use English character set.


    NOTE: All options above are CASE SENSITIVE.
          You can specify one or more options after a single '-',
          and as many '-' as you like, as long as a <blank> is placed in front of each '-'.

    @{b}@{u}Example:@{uu}@{ub}
      Filename      : "testfile"
      Filenote (old): "READ ME"
      Filenote (new): "Read me"

      The lines below works:

        @{fg fill}JustComm "testfile" -1l@{fg text}
	  or
        @{fg fill}JustComm "testfile" -1 -l@{fg text}

     ..but not these:

       @{fg fill}JustComm "testfile" -1L@{fg text}
         or
       @{fg fill}JustComm "testfile" -1 -L@{fg text}
@endnode


@node u_Details "JustComm documentation - Usage - Options - u"
@{b}u option:
---------@{ub}
    "Change letters to UPPERCASE."


    @{b}@{u}Example:@{uu}@{ub}
     Filename      : "TESTFILE"
     Filenote (old): "fIleNaMe.txt"
     Filenote (new): "FILENAME.TXT"

     Type in:
       @{fg fill}JustComm -u "testfile"@{fg text}
@endnode


@node l_Details "JustComm documentation - Usage - Options - l"
@{b}l option:
---------@{ub}
    "Change letters to lowercase."


    @{b}@{u}Example:@{uu}@{ub}
     Filename      : "TESTFILE"
     Filenote (old): "fIleNaMe.txt"
     Filenote (new): "filename.txt"

     Type in:
       @{fg fill}JustComm -l "testfile"@{fg text}
@endnode


@node 1_Details "JustComm documentation - Usage - Options - 1"
@{b}1 option:
---------@{ub}
    "Change 1st. letter to UPPERCASE."


    NOTE: If not the 1st. character is a letter, like f.ex. a number, 
          '!', '.', etc., JustComm will search for the first letter
          and make that letter uppercase.
          F.ex: "!filename.txt" will be changed to "!Filename.txt" 


    @{b}@{u}Example 1:@{uu}@{ub}
     Filename      : "TESTFILE"
     Filenote (old): "filename.txt"
     Filenote (new): "Filename.txt"
   
     Type in:
       @{fg fill}JustComm -1 "testfile"@{fg text}

   @{b}@{u}Example 2:@{uu}@{ub}
     Filename      : "TESTFILE"
     Filenote (old): "fIleNaMe.txt"
     Filenote (new): "Filename.txt"
   
     Here we want to make the first letter uppercase, and the rest lowercase.
     To achieve this, we must use both the -1 and -l option.
     Type in:
       @{fg fill}JustComm -1l "testfile"@{fg text}  
@endnode


@node r_Details "JustComm documentation - Usage - Options - r"
@{b}r option:
---------@{ub}
    "Change roman numerals to UPPERCASE (I, II, III, IV, V, etc.)."
 

    NOTE: This will not work if the roman numeral-characters in a filenote are 
          surrounded by letters. F.ex. the file "PacManiv" will be left unchanged,
          while "PacMan_iv" will change to "PacMan_IV".
          This is intentional, and is implemented this way to avoid
          f.ex. I's and V's in normal words to be mistaken as roman #'s.

    @{b}@{u}Example:@{uu}@{ub}
     Filename      : "TESTFILE"
     Filenote (old): "PacMan_iv"
     Filenote (new): "PacMan_IV"
     
     Type in:
       @{fg fill}JustComm -r "testfile"@{fg text}
@endnode


@node f_Details "JustComm documentation - Usage - Options - f"
@{b}f option:
---------@{ub}
    "Copy the filename."


    With this you can either:
       * replace the filenote with the filename,
       * replace parts of the filenote with the filename, 
       * insert the filename somewhere into the filenote etc.

    Together with the -i, -a, -b and SEL options, you have lots of possibilities.
    Below are some examples of how to use the option, and how to use it in combination with others.

    NOTE: The examples below don't show all possible combinations.

    NOTE: If used together with f.ex. the -u option, JustComm will
          firstly copy the filename into the filenote,
          and convert the copied text to uppercase afterwards.


    @{b}@{u}Example 1:@{uu}@{ub} Replace entire filenote with the filename

       Filename      : "myfile.txt"
       Filenote (old): "v1.15"
       Filenote (new): "myfile.txt"

       @{fg fill}JustComm -f "myfile.txt"@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 2:@{uu}@{ub} Replace the substring "." with the filename
       
       Filename      : "myfile.txt"
       Filenote (old): "v1.15"
       Filenote (new): "v1myfile.txt15"

       @{fg fill}JustComm -f SEL="." "myfile.txt"@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 3:@{uu}@{ub} Replace text after the substring "." with the filename
       
       Filename      : "myfile.txt"
       Filenote (old): "v1.15"
       Filenote (new): "v1.myfile.txt"

       @{fg fill}JustComm -fa SEL="." "myfile.txt"@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 4:@{uu}@{ub} Insert filename into the end of the filenote

       Filename      : "myfile.txt"
       Filenote (old): "v1.15"
       Filenote (new): "v1.15myfile.txt"

       @{fg fill}JustComm -fia "myfile.txt"@{fg text}
@endnode


@node t_Details "JustComm documentation - Usage - Options - t"
@{b}t option:
---------@{ub}
    "Remove control-characters."

    
    @{b}@{u}Example:@{uu}@{ub}
       Filename      : "Testfile"
       Filenote (old): "PacMan_IV›"
       Filenote (new): "PacMan_IV"

       To remove the CTRL-characters, type in:

         @{fg fill}JustComm -t "Testfile"@{fg text}
@endnode


@node b_Details "JustComm documentation - Usage - Options - b"
@{b}b option:
---------@{ub}
    "Select characters BEFORE a string."


    When using this option, you request JustComm to work with the string located:
     - before the complete filenote (if no SEL-option), or
     - before a selected substring in filenote (if SEL-option)
 
    @{b}@{u}Example 1:@{uu}@{ub}
     Filename      : "testfile"
     Filenote (old): "amiga_rulez"
     Filenote (new): "AMIGA_rulez"

     There are several ways to do this, but in this example
     we choose to make the letters before the "_" uppercase:
             
       @{fg fill}JustComm -bu SEL="_" "testfile"@{fg text}

  
    @{b}@{u}Example 2:@{uu}@{ub}
     Filename      : "testfile"
     Filenote (old): "the_AMIGA_rulez"
     Filenote (new): "AMIGA_rulez"

     Now, we choose to remove the text before "AMIGA":

       @{fg fill}JustComm -b SEL="AMIGA" REP="" "testfile"@{fg text}
@endnode


@node a_Details "JustComm documentation - Usage - Options - a"
@{b}a option:
---------@{ub}
    "Select characters AFTER a string."


    When using the -a option, you request JustComm to work with the string located:
     - after the complete filenote (if no SEL-option), or
     - after a selected substring in filenote (if SEL-option)
 

    @{b}@{u}Example 1:@{uu}@{ub}
     Filename      : "testfile"
     Filenote (old): "AMIGA_RULEZ"
     Filenote (new): "AMIGA_rulez"

     There are several ways to do this, but in this example
     we choose to make the letters after the "_" uppercase:
             
       @{fg fill}JustComm -al SEL="_" "testfile"@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 2:@{uu}@{ub}  
     Filename      : "testfile"
     Filenote (old): "AMIGA_rulez_____"
     Filenote (new): "AMIGA_rulez"

     Now, we choose to remove the text after "rulez":

       @{fg fill}JustComm -a SEL="rulez" REP="" "testfile"@{fg text}
@endnode


@node i_Details "JustComm documentation - Usage - Options - i"
@{b}i option:
---------@{ub}
    "Insert instead of replace."


    When using this option, new strings will be inserted, rather than replace existing strings.
    Use this in combination with the -b or -a options (before/after).
    If either -b or -a is used, the default is -a (after).
    However, the insert itself must be done by other options (-f, REP).


    @{b}@{u}Example 1:@{uu}@{ub}
     Filename      : "testfile"
     Filenote (old): "AMIGA"
     Filenote (new): "AMIGA_rulez"

     We choose to insert the text "_rulez" at the end:

       @{fg fill}JustComm -ia REP="_rulez" "testfile"@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 2:@{uu}@{ub}  
     Filename      : "testfile"
     Filenote (old): "AMIGA_rulez"
     Filenote (new): "The_AMIGA_rulez"

     We choose to insert the text "The_" at the start:

       @{fg fill}JustComm -ib REP="The_" "testfile"@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 3:@{uu}@{ub}
     Filename      : "testfile"
     Filenote (old): "AMIGA_forever"
     Filenote (new): "AMIGA_rulez_forever"

     We choose to insert the text "rulez_" after the text "AMIGA_":

       @{fg fill}JustComm -ia SEL="AMIGA_" REP="rulez_" "testfile"@{fg text}
@endnode


@node g_Details "JustComm documentation - Usage - Options - g"
@{b}g option:
---------@{ub}
    "Align text according to a given search string."


    This option is useful if you have lots of filenotes with the same type of information
    and a common separator between the elements, but the length of each element is different.

    Note: When using this option, a SEL option must always be included.


    @{b}@{u}Example:@{uu}@{ub}
     Let us say we have 3 files called "testfile01" to "testfile03".
     The filenotes is listed below:
      MAKE:Canon,MODEL:PowerShot S3IS,ISO:50,WB:AUTO
      MAKE:Nikon,MODEL:CoolpixL10,ISO:AUTO,WB:AUTO
      MAKE:Unknown,MODEL:?,ISO=?,WB:?

     We want the filenotes to look like this:
      MAKE:Canon  ,MODEL:PowerShot S3IS,ISO:50  ,WB:AUTO
      MAKE:Nikon  ,MODEL:CoolpixL10    ,ISO:AUTO,WB:AUTO
      MAKE:Unknown,MODEL:?             ,ISO=?   ,WB:?

     Much easier to read the filenotes now, isn't it?

     This will be achieved by telling JustComm to align the "," character:

       @{fg fill}JustComm -g SEL="," "testfile|*|"@{fg text}
@endnode


@node Sens_Details "JustComm documentation - Usage - Options - S"
@{b}S option:
---------@{ub}
    "Make string matching of filenotes case sensitive."


    When using this option, filenote matching is performed case sensitive.
    This means that if you f.ex. search for a string "CLI",
    the string "CLI" will be matched, but not "Cli".

    @{b}NOTE:@{ub} Doesn't have any effect on filename searches.
@endnode


@node e_Details "JustComm documentation - Usage - Options - e"
@{b}e option:
---------@{ub}
    "Use english character set."


    With this option set, only the letters a-z and A-Z will be treated as letters.
    Use this if you encounter problems with the default character set.
@endnode



@node Advanced_Options "JustComm documentation - Usage - Advanced Options"
@{b}Advanced options:
-----------------@{ub}

    @{"SEL=" link SEL_Details}"<string>"   Select substring
    @{"FLU=" link FLU_Details}"<string>"   Make 1st. letter after 1 of these uppercase
    @{"REP=" link REP_Details}"<string>"   Replace
    @{"ZER=" link ZER_Details}<number>     Leading zeros
    @{"EXP=" link EXP_Details}"<file>"     Export filenotes to file
    @{"EXO=" link EXO_Details}"<file>"     As EXP, but overwrites existing file
    @{"EXA=" link EXA_Details}"<file>"     As EXP, but appends existing file
    @{"IMP=" link IMP_Details}"<file>"     Import filenotes from file
    @{"&&"   link NEW_Details}               New adjustment

    NOTE: All of the advanced options above are CASE INSENSITIVE. Iow., both rep= and REP= works.
          However, no spaces are allowed either before or after the '='.

    NOTE: There is a big difference between the strings " " and "".
          " " means one blank character, while the "" means an EMPTY string.
@endnode

@node SEL_Details "JustComm documentation - Usage - Advanced Options - SEL"
@{b}SEL option:
-----------@{ub}
    "Select a substring in filenotes."


    Select only the substrings which matches the given string.
    Wildcards are supported. These are:
     |*| - 0 or more occurrences of any character
     |?| - 1 occurrence of any character
     |#| - 1 or more digits
     |U| - 1 uppercase letter placed immediatly after a lowercase one.
 
    NOTE: Matching is CASE INSENSITIVE as default, but can be
          overridden to CASE SENSITIVE using the -S option.


    The examples below may seem somewhat strange as long as we only change 1 filenote at a time.
    It's when you uses JustComm on several files you will discover the strength of these wildcards.


    @{b}@{u}Example 1:@{uu}@{ub} The |*| wildcard

         Filename      : "testfile"
         Filenote (old): "My_fIle_no-01.txt"
         Filenote (new): "My_File_no-01.txt"

         We choose to change the substring "_file_". Type in the following:
    
         @{fg fill}JustComm "testfile" SEL="_|*|_" -1l@{fg text}
           or
         @{fg fill}JustComm "testfile" SEL="_file_" -1l@{fg text}                    


    @{b}@{u}Example 2:@{uu}@{ub} The |?| wildcard

         Filename      : "testfile"
         Filenote (old): "My_file_no-01.txt"
         Filenote (new): "My_file_no.txt"

         We choose to remove the 3 characters in front of ".txt":
    
         @{fg fill}JustComm "testfile" SEL="|?||?||?|.txt" REP=".txt"@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 3:@{uu}@{ub} The |#| wildcard
 
         Filename      : "testfile"
         Filenote (old): "My_fIle_no_01.txt"
         Filenote (new): "My_File.txt"

         Type in the following:
    
         @{fg fill}JustComm "testfile" SEL="_no_|#|" REP=""@{fg text}
           or
         @{fg fill}JustComm "testfile" SEL="_no_01" REP=""@{fg text}                    


    @{b}@{u}Example 4:@{uu}@{ub} The |U| wildcard
 
         Filename      : "testfile"
         Filenote (old): "MyFileCommand"
         Filenote (new): "My file command"

         We choose to insert a space in front of each "subword":
    
         @{fg fill}JustComm "testfile" SEL="|U|" -ib REP=" " && -1l@{fg text}
@endnode

@node FLU_Details "JustComm documentation - Usage - Advanced Options - FLU"
@{b}FLU option:
-----------@{ub}
    "Make the first letter after 1 of the specified characters uppercase."

 
    NOTE: CASE INSENSITIVE matching is default, but can be overridden to
          CASE SENSITIVE matching with the -S option.

    @{b}@{u}Example 1:@{uu}@{ub}
     Filename      : "testfile"
     Filenote (old): "This is my file. i want to change the note! see ya!"
     Filenote (new): "This is my file. I want to change the note! See ya!"

     To do this, type in the following:

       @{fg fill}JustComm "testfile" FLU=".!"@{fg text}
@endnode

@node REP_Details "JustComm documentation - Usage - Advanced Options - REP"
@{b}REP option:
-----------@{ub}
    "Replace strings in filenote."


    Replaces either the complete filenote or selected substring with the given one.

    When used in combination with the -i (insert) option and -b (before)/-a (after) options, 
    JustComm will insert the new String before or after the selected one.
 
    When used in combination with the -b or -a, but without the -i option,
    JustComm will replace the text before or after the selected substring.

    You can do a lot with this option in combination with others.
    See also @{"SEL=" link SEL_Details}.

    
    @{b}@{u}Example 1:@{uu}@{ub} Search and Replace

       Filename      : "testfile"
       Filenote (old): "This_is_my_File.txt"
       Filenote (new): "This_is_Your_File.txt"

       Type in the following:
         @{fg fill}JustComm "testfile" SEL="my" REP="Your"@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 2:@{uu}@{ub} Replace complete filenote with a new one

       Filename      : "testfile"
       Filenote (old): "This_is_my_File.txt"
       Filenote (new): "Testfile.txt"

       Type in the following:       
         @{fg fill}JustComm "testfile" REP="Testfile.txt"@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 3:@{uu}@{ub} Insert text after the end of the filenote

       Filename      : "testfile"
       Filenote (old): "This is my File"
       Filenote (new): "This is my File, keep away!"

       Type in the following:       
         @{fg fill}JustComm "testfile" -ia REP=", keep away!"@{fg text}       


    @{b}@{u}Example 4:@{uu}@{ub} Insert text after a substring in the filenote

       Filename      : "testfile"
       Filenote (old): "This is my File"
       Filenote (new): "This is my very own File"

       Type in the following:       
         @{fg fill}JustComm "testfile" -ia SEL="my " REP="very own "@{fg text}       


    @{b}@{u}Example 5:@{uu}@{ub} Replace all text after a substring

       Filename      : "testfile"
       Filenote (old): "This is my File, keep away!"
       Filenote (new): "This is my File"

       Type in the following:       
         @{fg fill}JustComm "testfile" -a SEL="File" REP=""@{fg text}
@endnode

@node ZER_Details "JustComm documentation - Usage - Advanced Options - ZER"
@{b}ZER option:
-----------@{ub}
    "Include leading zeros in numbers."

    
    You can choose between 1 and 9 digits.
    If the found number contains more digits than the number you request (excluding the leading 0's),
    JustComm will remove leading zeros (if they exist).
    If the found number countains less digits than requested, leading zeros will be added.


    @{b}@{u}Example 1:@{uu}@{ub}
     Filename      : "testfile"
     Filenote (old): "The number is 34 and 10000"
     Filenote (new): "The number is 0034 and 10000"

     Type in the following:

       @{fg fill}JustComm "testfile" ZER=4@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 2:@{uu}@{ub}
     Filename      : "testfile"
     Filenote (old): "The number is 0034"
     Filenote (new): "The number is 34"

     Type in the following:

       @{fg fill}JustComm "testfile" ZER=1@{fg text}
         or
       @{fg fill}JustComm "testfile" ZER=2@{fg text}
@endnode

@node EXP_Details "JustComm documentation - Usage - Advanced Options - EXP"
@{b}EXP option:
-----------@{ub}
    "Export filenotes to a file."


    Useful if you want to:
        * create a backup of your filenotes.
        * export your filenotes to poor filesystems without filenote support.

    The file format is the same as PC programs like "Total Commander" accepts.
    This makes it possible to let "Total Commander" show the filenotes.

    NOTE: If a file with the same name already exists, JustComm returns an error message.

    NOTE: If filenotes contains LF-characters, all text after the LF-character will be moved to
          the next line in the export file. This may cause compatibility issues with other programs.
          To avoid problems, it's recommended to always remove CTRL-characters before export.


    @{b}@{u}Example:@{uu}@{ub}
     We want to export all our filenotes to a file called "DESCRIPT.ION":

       @{fg fill}JustComm "|*|" EXP="DESCRIPT.ION"@{fg text}
@endnode

@node EXO_Details "JustComm documentation - Usage - Advanced Options - EXO"
@{b}EXO option:
-----------@{ub}
    "Export filenotes to a file, and overwrite the output file if it already exist."


    Works as @{"EXP=" link EXP_Details}, but overwrites the output file if it already exists.
    If the file doesn't exist, a new file will be created.
@endnode

@node EXA_Details "JustComm documentation - Usage - Advanced Options - EXA"
@{b}EXA option:
-----------@{ub}
    "Export filenotes to a file, and append to the output file if it already exist."


    Works as @{"EXP=" link EXP_Details}, but appends to the existing output file if it already exists.
    If the file doesn't exist, a new file will be created.
@endnode

@node IMP_Details "JustComm documentation - Usage - Advanced Options - IMP"
@{b}IMP option:
-----------@{ub}
    "Import filenotes from a file."


    Reads filenotes from a file, and changes the filenotes (same file format as the one @{"EXP=" link EXP_Details} creates).
    This option comes in handy when:      
        * copying files from poor file systems which doesn't support filenotes,
          and store them on your Amiga as real filenotes (nothing beats the real thing, eh?).
        * efficiently mass-update filenotes based on misc. sources (f.ex. URL's).
        * you want to restore your filenotes.

    You don't need to specify any filenames when using this option, 
    as all filenames are specified in the import file.
    However, you can both import and f.ex. change letters to UPPERCASE (or any other operation)
    in the same operation. This is possible because JustComm does the import first.
    If you want to do such a thing, you have to specify the filenames as normal to JustComm.
    

    @{b}@{u}Example 1:@{uu}@{ub}
     We want to import filenotes from the file "DESCRIPT.ION" we created in the @{"EXP=" link EXP_Details} example:

       @{fg fill}JustComm IMP="DESCRIPT.ION"@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 2:@{uu}@{ub}
     ..and we also want to make the filenotes look better:

       @{fg fill}JustComm IMP="DESCRIPT.ION" -1lrt FLU="." && SEL="|U|" -ib REP=" "@{fg text}
@endnode

@node NEW_Details "JustComm documentation - Usage - Advanced Options - &&"
@{b}&& option:
----------@{ub}
    "New adjustment."


    Makes it possible to do a new adjustment of the filenote in the same go,
    as otherwise had to be done by running JustComm several times.
    Iow., this option increases flexibility, and saves you time.
    More than one '&&' is allowed, with a maximum of 7.
    
    Note: The options are individual within each '&&', but the filenames aren't.
          This option comes in handy when you normally have to run JustComm
          with the same file(s) more than once to achieve your goal. 


    @{b}@{u}Example:@{uu}@{ub}
     Filename      : "testfile"
     Filenote (old): "mY oWn cli-comMand"
     Filenote (new): "My very own CLI-command"

     Now, type in the following:

       @{fg fill}JustComm "testfile" -1l && SEL="CLI" -u && SEL="My" -ia REP=" very"@{fg text}

     Without the &&-option, you have to perform several operations on the same file like this:
  
       JustComm "testfile" -1l 
       JustComm "testfile" SEL="CLI" -u
       JustComm "testfile" SEL="My" -ia REP=" very" 

     This is waste of time, in addition to unnecessary writing to the disk.
@endnode


@node Filenames "JustComm documentation - Usage - Filenames"
@{b}Filename(s):
------------@{ub}
    One or more filenames can be chosen, but is optional when the @{"IMP=" link IMP_Details} option is chosen.
    Each filename must be enclosed by quotes ("), and a space (" ") is not needed to separate them.
    If you choose more than one filename, each file has to be specified after each other.
    This means options or advanced options cannot be placed between the filenames.

    JustComm supports wildcards in filenames. These are:
     |*| - 0 or more occurrences of any character
     |?| - 1 occurrence of any character
     |#| - 1 or more digits
 
    Note: Matching of files is always CASE INSENSITIVE, even if you have chosen the @{"  S  " link Sens_Details} option.


    Example: Suppose we have the following files in the RAM-disk, and 
             want to change the first letter in the filenotes to uppercase:
             RAM:file1
             RAM:file2
             RAM:file3
             RAM:file4new
             RAM:newfile

    Example 1: JustComm "RAM:file1" "RAM:file2" "RAM:file3" "RAM:newfile" -1
    Example 2: JustComm "RAM:file|?|" -1
    Example 3: JustComm "RAM:file|*|" -1
    Example 4: JustComm "RAM:file|#|" -1
    Example 5: JustComm "RAM:|*|" -1

    Example 1 speaks for itself.
    Example 2 choose file1, file2 and file3.
    Example 3 choose file1, file2, file3 and file4new.
    Example 4 choose file1, file2 and file3.
    Example 5 choose all files in RAM.

    Note: JustComm does not support recursion.
          This means if a directory is chosen, it will not perform any actions on files/dirs in it.

    @{b}@{u}Tip: Directory recursion with Directory Opus@{uu}@{ub}
      If you are using JustComm from Directory Opus, Opus will make recursion possible
      (you have to set the flag "Recursive dirs" in Dir. Opus' Button Editor).
      Note that Directory Opus will not rename the directories itself when "Recursive dirs" is on.
      This trick works both with Directory Opus 4 & 5.
@endnode


@node Tips "JustComm documentation - Tips"
@{b}Tips & Hints
------------@{ub}

    * @{b}Displaying the usage@{ub}
      When starting JustComm with no arguments, it will display the Usage and available arguments.
      The same thing happens if there is an error in the argument string.


    * @{b}Wildcards (|*|, |?|. |#|, |U|)@{ub}
         * can be used both when searching for filenames or selecting filenote substrings.
           NOTE: The |U| cannot be used for searching filenames.
         * all wildcard types can be combined with each other
         * you can use as many wildcards as you like
         * can be combined with normal characters


    * @{b}Directory recursion@{ub}
      This is not supported by JustComm.
      However, Directory Opus can be configured to take care of this.
      See own topic @{"Usage - Filenames" link Filenames}.


    * @{b}Input redirection@{ub}
      This is standard AmigaDOS functionality, and works the same way as other CLI commands.
      It makes it possible to pass arguments to JustComm via a file instead of typing them in by hand.
      To use this functionality, use the standard "<" character as shown in the example below.

      Example:
        Here are the contents of a file called Filewithargs.txt:
          @{fg fill}"File1" "File2" -u@{fg text}
        
        You can pass the contents of this file to JustComm by typing:
          @{fg fill}JustComm <Filewithargs.txt@{fg text}


    * @{b}Output redirection@{ub}
      You can send the output of the command to a file instead of the console, if you want to.
      This is standard AmigaDOS functionality.

      Example:
        @{fg fill}JustComm "|*|" >RAM:JustComm_Output.txt@{fg text}


    * @{b}Character set problems@{ub}
      If you experience any problems with certain characters, try the -e option.
      With this option set, JustComm will not change case'ing on other characters than a-z and A-Z.


    * @{b}Make the most out of JustComm@{ub}
      See the attached Directory Opus 5 buttons too see examples of how to use JustComm correct,
      or to get ideas of how to get the most out of this neat command.
@endnode


@node History "JustComm documentation - History"
@{b}History
-------@{ub}

    @{b}@{u}v1.16 (7.Mar.2010). Changes:@{ub}@{uu}
      * Corrected bugs related to the |#| and |U| wildcards. Details:
           * |#|: When choosing files by putting this wildcard last,
                  JustComm selected more files than expected.
                  Example: 
                     JustComm "File|#|" -u
                       ...selected f.ex. "File1", "File2" & "File1a"
                       ...while the expected selection was "File1" & "File2"
           * |U|: When using this wildcard in your SEL-string,
                  combined with the -i, -a and REP-options
                  (insert a string after each lower->UPPERCASE change),
                  this sometimes didn't work.
                  It worked fine for the 1st, 3rd, 5th etc. occurrence,
                  but not the 2nd., 4th, 6th etc.
      * Corrected a bug related to the export option (EXP/EXA/EXO). Details:
        Files which couldn't be processed because of an error
        were included in the exported file.
      * Improved performance. When inserting text after a selected string,
        execution is faster now compared to v1.15.


    @{b}@{u}v1.15 (3.Jan.2010). Changes:@{ub}@{uu}
      * Standard input redirection is now supported.
        This means you can let JustComm read the args from a textfile.
        F.ex.: JustComm <MyArgs.txt
      * Max number of allowed &&'s is increased from 4 to 7.
      * New option ZER (leading zeros in numbers).
      * New options EXP, EXO, EXA (export filenotes to a file).
      * New option IMP (import filenotes from a file).
      * New option -g (align).
      * More flexible search&replace functionality:
           * New option -S. Makes it possible to do case sensitive searches.
           * New option -i (insert).
           * New option -b (select before).
           * New option -a (select after).
           * Added support for 2 new wildcards:
                * |#| : Searches for a number (sequence of 1 or more digits).
                * |U| : Searches for an uppercase letter placed
                        immediatly after a lowercase letter.
      * Removed obsolete options:
           * The -c option (make copyright-sign (C) uppercase).
             Tip: Use Search&Replace instead.
           * The option to choose "any character set".
             Note: "Any character set" is still default.


    @{b}@{u}v1.12 (12.Feb.2000). Changes:@{ub}@{uu}
      * Fixed a bug: JustComm seemed to abort processing if a file 
        couldn't be found or a file was in use. This bug only occurred 
        on Amigas with kickstart 2.0 or better. It worked fine on Amigas 
        with kickstart older than 2.0.
      * Fixed a bug: When selecting substrings using the '|?|' wildcard,
        the substring could in some cases not be found.    
      * Internal changes.


    @{b}@{u}v1.11 (7.Dec.1999). Changes:@{ub}@{uu}
      * Fixed a bug which occurred if replace-strings (REP) were too long.
      * Internal improvements.


    @{b}@{u}v1.10 (4.Dec.1999). New functionality:@{ub}@{uu}
      * New option -f (copy filename to filenote).
      * New option && (multiple changes of filenotes).
      * Replace complete filenote or selected substrings with a new one.
      * Supports wildcards in filename(s) and when selecting substrings.
      * Some other changes.


    @{b}@{u}v1.00 (6th. Aug. 1999):@{ub}@{uu}
      * Initial Aminet release.
@endnode


@node Technical "JustComm documentation - Technical"
@{b}Technical info
--------------@{ub}
    
    This program is written in pure assembler.
    I have prioritized speed, memory efficiency, compact executable,
    compatibility (I want it to work on all Amigas), and it is meant to be 
    both user friendly and flexible.

    And of course: Robustness. It's rock solid! I don't want to mess up your harddrive...
    
    For now, it lacks a GUI, but together with Directory Opus 5,
    the included buttons pretty much makes up for this.
@endnode


